<div id="banner">
	<h1>My First Usenet Post</h1>
</div>

<div class="content">
<p>I just found my first-ever post to USENET. I was eight years old, not yet old enough to have grown out of AOL, and read the newsgroup of one of my favorite TV Show&#8217;s &#8220;Beakman&#8217;s World&#8221;. You&#8217;ll have to excuse my poor spelling and punctuation &#8212; this clearly was one of my first &#8216;Net experiences. So, thanks to Google Groups, I can now read <a href="http://groups.google.com/groups?hl=en&amp;selm=349ruq%24eom%40search01.news.aol.com">my very first post</a>.</p>

<p>It&#8217;s short, isn&#8217;t it? Notice how even then I had two email addresses. Unfortunately, Google doesn&#8217;t seem to have <a href="mid:BPOSTOW.94Jul11120335@ringding.cs.umd.edu">the message I was replying to</a>.</p>

<p>I remember talking to my father about how the creators of a competing show, &#8220;Bill Nye: The Science Guy&#8221;, kept asking the newsgroup to explain what they liked so much about Beakman&#8217;s World. I remember being rather puzzled at the question, as it just seemed obvious to me that Beakman&#8217;s was better, even though I had no reason for that decision.</p>

<p>Later on, it seems I shared an account with my two brothers, who <a href="http://groups.google.com/groups?selm=32DEA3CD.FE%40www.substantial.com">were looking for games</a> and after that I started <a href="http://groups.google.com/groups?selm=J_aL3.14640%24Od.47050%40news.rdc1.il.home.com">asking about DC-Nets</a> (a question which I still haven&#8217;t gotten a good answer to).</p>

<p>Anyway, enough memories for one night.</p>

<p>Some of you might find <a href="http://groups.google.com/groups?selm=349ruq%24eom%40search01.news.aol.com&amp;output=gplain">the full text</a> interesting. Here it is, for posterity:</p>

<p><code>
From: aaronsw@aol.com (Aaron Sw)
